%I A283056 #25 Mar 17 2026 23:56:41
%S A283056 0,7,9,11,11,13,13
%N A283056 Size of the smallest polyomino that admits a hole of size n.
%C A283056 The task here is to surround a hole of size n with the least number of squares. The hole is another polyomino, so we can obtain a lower bound using A027709: minimal perimeter of polyomino with n square cells. We need an extra 3 (or more) diagonal cells to surround any hole. Hence a(n) >= A027709(n) + 3 = 2*ceiling(2*sqrt(n)) + 3.
%C A283056 For rectangular holes we can obtain an upper bound using A262767: minimum perimeter of a rectangle with area n and integer sides. Hence a(n) <= A262767(n) + 3.
%C A283056 Perhaps a(n) is actually equal to A027709(n)+3?
%C A283056 From _Peter Exley_, Mar 08 2026: (Start)
%C A283056 Upper bounds: a(7) <= 15, a(8) <= 15, a(9) <= 15, a(10) <= 17, a(11) <= 17, a(12) <= 17, a(13) <= 19, a(14) <= 19, a(15) <= 19, a(16) <= 19, a(17) <= 21, a(18) <= 21, a(19) <= 21, a(20) <= 21, found by simulated annealing with Numba JIT compilation. All 14 values match the conjectured formula a(n) = A027709(n) + 3. Solver matches known values for a(0) through a(6).
%C A283056 Conjecture: a(n) = A027709(n) + 3 (upper bounds matching formula verified for n = 1..20).
%C A283056 Proof sketch for a(n) = A027709(n) + 3: Let H be the hole (an n-omino with minimal perimeter P = A027709(n)). Let B be the set of cells edge-adjacent to H. Then (1) each concave corner of H causes one cell of B to be adjacent to two perimeter edges, so |B| = P - ccv where ccv is the number of concave corners; (2) B decomposes into exactly 4 + ccv connected components (4 for the "sides", plus one extra component per concave corner where the boundary bends inward); (3) to connect k components into a single polyomino requires exactly k - 1 bridge cells. Thus a(n) = |B| + (4 + ccv - 1) = (P - ccv) + ccv + 3 = P + 3. Verified computationally for all polyominoes up to 7 cells. (End)
%H A283056 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A283056">Solver code, data, and figures</a>, GitHub.
%e A283056 For n=1, we have a single square hole, so a(1)=7.
%e A283056 For n=2, we have a domino hole, so a(2)=9.
%e A283056 For n=3, we can use either an L or V tromino hole, so a(3)=11.
%e A283056 For n=4, we use the square tetromino hole, so a(4)=11.
%e A283056 For n=5, we use the P pentomino hole, so a(5)=13.
%e A283056 For n=6, we use the 2 X 3 rectangle hole, so a(6)=13.
%Y A283056 Cf. A027709.
%K A283056 nonn,more,changed
%O A283056 0,2
